<article class="comment" id="comment5765679" data-author="users/142550" data-subject="comments/5765679" data-dislikes="0" data-id="5765679">
<p class="avatar"><a rel="nofollow" title="zekepliskin" href="/users/zekepliskin"><img class="framed lazy" src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHZpZXdCb3g9IjAgMCA4MCA4MCI+PC9zdmc+" width="80" height="80" data-original="https://images.nintendolife.com/users/142550/avatar.jpg?v=1609849790" alt="zekepliskin" /></a></p>
<div class="detail"><ul class="info"><li class=" first"><a class="num" rel="nofollow" href="news/2020/08/random_nintendo_posts_new_image_of_mario_in_the_sunshine_internet_goes_wild_again#comment5765679">159</a></li><li><a rel="nofollow" class="username accent" title="zekepliskin" href="/users/zekepliskin">zekepliskin</a></li><li class=" last"><time class="date age " datetime="2020-08-13T07:18:12+00:00"><span>Thu 13th Aug 2020</span></time></li></ul>
<section class="text">
<p>It's probably as simple as, this is pre made promotional material, there's a heatwave, Nintendo are using this to make a temperature based gag out of it.</p><p>Typical Internet rumour mill/false hope/exaggeration cycle. This is exactly the kind of attitude that leads to &quot;Sony are releasing a new handheld console ZOMG!?&quot; nonsense just because they filed a patent for something vaguely related to it that might never be made anyway. Sometimes companies just do these things to do them; they're not grand masters of foreshadowing whose every social media post has some hidden meaning or ulterior motive. As always, people just need to get a grip.</p></section>
